<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=100679432782711></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f100679432782711><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=6&mid=100679432782711>RANT: Die and Retry</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=6&mid=100679432782711#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=83710><span id=Scholar>jcasetnl</span></a>, <span id=Scholar>Scholar</span><br><span id=notbold>153 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Mon, Nov 26th 12:05 PM 2001</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent<span id=notbold>[2.90]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>Today's rant is about a phrase common to most old skool gamers out there: 'die and retry'.&nbsp;&nbsp;It refers to those games that due to poor design, force the player to die meaninglessly or unfairly just to 'learn' where traps are, what to kill, where to go, etc.  <br><br>A classic 'die and retry' game was Dragon's Lair, the old Laserdisc game.  You tried your best to do what you felt made sense but inevitably you'd die.  Then you'd go do it again (i.e. retry) and just choose something else randomly.  You keep doing this until you happen upon the correct choice.  In a lot of cases the correct choice made no logical sense.  As you can imagine, this was an expensive and boring proposition.<br><br>Well, I've known there's a lot of die and retry in EQ for a long time now, but lately it has particularly started to get on my nerves and it really hurts the game as a whole.  <br><br>It boils down to basically three components: 1) Agro management 2) An aging, not truly 3-dimensional 3d engine, and 3) Pathing.  There are certainly other factors (gaurds con'ing light blue but hitting for 90s in Lake Rathe to my 27 Paladin, for example) but I think these are three big ones.<br><br>First, agro management.  I'm not talking about keeping agro on the main tank, I'm speaking with respect to pulling and training.  Agro management isn't, in itself, the problem but it becomes a huge problem when you take into account 2 and 3.<br><br>Speaking of 2, EQ's 3D engine is a dinosaur.  This is the single biggest problem with the game if you ask me.  For example, I was in unrest and went to the roof of one of the forward spires.  I lulled the mob on the terrace thingy and waited until he was furthest from his friends then attempted to engage him.  Suddenly I'm being hit by a mob that I cannot see.  Turns out the mob in the base of the spire, nearly THREE FLOORS below me was hitting me.  He then went on to agro the Torklar Battle Master, also nearly 3 floors away.  Result: big train, everybody run.  Thus, applying a somewhat logical approach to keeping a single mob's agro under control is useless and meaningless.  So, I go back and try from some other position to see what happens.  Die and retry.<br><br>In another case I was pulling centaurs to the bridge to solo.  One went under the bridge UNDER WATER and was still hitting me.  <br><br>This is not called 3D, folks, this is called 2D, and is essentially how old, outdated engines such as Doom, Doom 2 and their many clones operated in the early days of the FPS.<br><br>Also on the subject of the 3D engine, there is no true concept of solid objects.  They don't exist.  It's that simple.  If the EQ programmers don't specifically change the agro tendencies of a mob, it does not matter if a 'solid' object exists between him and his friends.  It does not matter if they're on a different floor.  They will still agro on you.  <br><br>And there are the ever more familiar examples of mobs walking through solid objects, such as trees and buildings.  Why have a building there at all?  Put the vendor in an open air stall so at least that lion that starts hitting me in the middle of a sale makes a bit of sense.  <br><br>I've already pointed out the example of Unrest as one where mobs will agro and hit you from over a floor away.  But look at Split Paw.  Near the entrance is a set of double doors with two spawns that guard it.  Agro one and the gnolls just inside the doors will not agro even though they are scant 'feet' away.  Hey that actually makes sense if the doors are closed.  But how do you figure out what will agro and what will not?  Die and retry.<br><br>But lets add pathing to the mix.  For those of you that don't know, pathing is the 'path' a mob will take, either in its normal walking route or when it agros and chases.  Outdoor zones don't suffer nearly as much from pathing problems mainly because it's mitigated by more room to fight.  But in dungeons?  You smack a mob to either pull it or kill it, back up a bit so his friends don't join in and the mob runs some crazy loop around the dungeon, agro'ing EVERYTHING.  Now you're dead.  But wait!  Hit his friend right next to him, and that mob will come right to you and agro nothing.  How do figure out which is which?  Die and retry.  <br><br>A few weeks ago I talked at length about how I and one other Paladin cleared the 2nd floor of Befallen.  This was before the recent nerf.  For just two 20s Paladins, this is not an easy thing to do.  A lot of thought went into it, sure, but at the same time there was a lot of die and retry as well, I now realize.  We knew the pathing from experience and that made a big part of the difference.  We knew the respawn times and we knew where the powerful stuff was.  In and of itself, the pathing of befallen makes little sense, but at least you aren't hit by mobs on different floors.<br><br>At this point, let me say that experience and familiarity should play a part in playing EQ, and I'm not implying otherwise.  One dungeon *should* have a different feel and different agro rules from another.  But there's the key word: rules.  There should be at least some consistency and logic in the way a dungeon plays.  Otherwise?  Die and Retry.<br><br>And is die and retry totally useless?  Certainly not.  A player should occasionally get nailed by a trap or hidden npc.  That's part of the fun.  But when virtually every aspect of a dungeon crawl turns into a crapshoot and skill is an after thought, that's when it becomes a problem.<br><br>So to sum up, we have a game that centers heavily around agro management but is severely bugged in ways that make this impossible except through learning 'the hard way'.  <br><br>In my experience this has caused players to either avoid dungeons altogether or only crawl dungeons with ridiculously overwhelming numbers or overpowered characters.  <br><br>Things that need to change?  Fix the pathing.  The 3d engine is a lost cause so at least make the pathing slightly intelligent.  In addition, calming spells should become very low resist and SHOULD AFFECT PATHING.  They should work with at least 80% certainty againt blue mobs or lower and should, cause the mob to come straight to you when agro'd as opposed to it running its circuit to gather friends.  Currently, calming spells are practically useless because if they fail everything agros.  If they suceed, there is still a very good chance that everything agros when you pull.  Players should have useful tools to manage agro.  Spells that do next to nothing to control aggression are useless.<br><br>/rant off<br><br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 >&nbsp;</td><td align=right valign=bottom>
	   <span style='font-weight: normal; font-size: 9px;'>[<a href=#top>Top</a>]</span></tr>
	   </form></table><ul>

